During WWII women started working outside the home for the first time as a massive wave in American history. Decades later, we were still being harassed, paid less and taken advantage of... The Equal Rights Amendment (first introduced in 1923 but didn't pass in congress until 1971) which provided legal equality of the sexes and prohibited discrimination by sex in the workplace was met with a strong conservative push back that led to it’s demise. 50 years later, women are still fighting to be equal. In this country, a woman has never held the highest office in government, not as President or Vice President. We have been secretary of state THREE times in the last 240 some years (a trend that didn’t start until the mid 90’s). We make up about 19% of congress, even though we make up about 51% of the population. We live in one of the only industrialized countries to still not mandate paid leave for women once they have children, one of the only countries where now apparently the byproduct of being raped can be considered a “pre-existing condition” if states choose so. What I am saying is WAKE UP, you are far from even, and we have so far to go. We can pretend that we’re equal, equal in gender, race, religion, but sadly that is not, and never has been true. To think 100 years ago women didn’t even have the right to vote should clarify this issue for you. Minorities and the poor are still being stripped of their voting rights by legislation drawn up by states trying to oppress. Stand up, speak up, and PAY ATTENTION. #equality #genderequality #girlboss #thefutureisfemale #giveafuck
